Dimocarpus longan var. longan

   [5349.jpg]
   Authority Lour.
   Family Magnoliopsida:Rosidae:Sapindales:Sapindaceae
   Synonyms Euphoria longan Steud., Euphoria longana Lamk (1792),
   Nephelium longana Cambess.
   Common names longan, longanie, oeil de dragon, len keng, kyet mouk,
   mien, lam nhai, nam nhai, lamyai pa, lahm-yai, nam:nhan
   Editor
   Ecocrop code 5349

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A small to medium-sized tree usually reaching 10-20 m
   in height, sometimes buttressed and with a 2-4 m deep root system. The
   fruits are broad-ellipsoid to globular, yellow-brown and 1-3 cm in
   diameter. USES The fruits are mainly eaten fresh, but the are also used
   in canning industries. The fruits can also be dried and used to prepare
   a refreshing drink. A liqueur is made by macerating the logan flesh in
   alcohol. The seeds are used as a shampoo. Both the seeds and the fruit
   flesh have several medicinal uses. The timber is fairly hard and
   useful. KILLING T Young trees are frost tender, and mature trees will
   only tolerate -3 to -5째C for few hours. GROWING PERIOD Perennial tree.
   Begins to bear 4-5 years after sowing. Economical life about 25 years.
   COMMON NAMES Longan, Longane, Longanier, Lungan, Longyen, Lengkeng,
   Lamyai, Lingeng, Oeil de dragon, Kyet mouk, Mien, Lam nhai, Nam nhai,
   Lamyai pa, Nham. FURTHER INF Scientific synonym: Euphoria longana,
   Nephelium longana, Dimocarpus longan. Longan is native of southern
   China, Myanmar and perhaps also southwestern India and Sri Lanka. It
   can be grown at elevations up to 1500 m in southwestern India, up to
   900 m in Giava and up to 1300 m in Bengala. It needs chilling
   temperatures of about 7-12째C, or a 2-3 months period with temperatures
   about 15-22째C and a short dry period to stimulate flowering. From fruit
   set and onwards night temperatures should not be above 20-25째C. In
   Thailand trees yield from 1-6 t/ha or up to 120 kg per tree, but large
   trees may yield up to 200-300 kg. Mentioned as a useful agroforestry
   species.

